A user enters www.foobar.com in their browser. The browser asks DNS for the IP address of the domain name. DNS returns the IP address of the HAProxy load balancer. HAProxy receives the request and sends it to one of the two backend servers.

HAProxy is added to distribute incoming traffic between multiple servers. This prevents one web server from receiving every request and allows the infrastructure to handle more users.

The load balancer uses the Round Robin algorithm. It sends the first request to Server 2, the second request to Server 3, then returns to Server 2, and continues alternating between the available servers.

The two backend servers are configured as an Active-Active setup. Both servers are running and can receive traffic at the same time. HAProxy distributes requests between them.

In an Active-Passive setup, only one server actively handles requests. The second server stays on standby and is used only when the active server fails. Active-Active is better for distributing traffic, while Active-Passive is mainly used for failover.

Each backend server contains Nginx, the application server, and a copy of the application files. This is necessary because either server must be able to handle a user request independently.

Nginx receives the HTTP request from HAProxy and forwards dynamic requests to the application server. The application server runs the application logic using the application files.

The MySQL databases are configured in a Primary-Replica cluster. The Primary database receives write operations such as INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE. It then replicates its data changes to the Replica database.

The Primary database is the source of truth for writes. The Replica database copies data from the Primary and can be used for read queries, backups, or recovery. The application must send writes to the Primary database. It may send read-only queries to the Replica database.

This infrastructure still has important issues:

HAProxy is a SPOF. If the load balancer fails, users cannot reach either backend server.
The MySQL Primary is a SPOF for writes. If it fails, the application cannot create or modify data.
Each server still contains several services. If one backend server fails, its web server, application server, and database are affected together.
There is no firewall to restrict unwanted traffic to the servers.
There is no HTTPS configuration, so data may be transmitted without encryption.
There is no monitoring system to detect failures, high CPU usage, errors, or slow services.
